{"types":[{"section":"\n{{fr-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|fr|transitive}} to [[hate]]\n\n====Usage notes====\n* In Standard French, the ''h'' of ''haïr'' is aspirated; thus, [[elision]]s of vowels and [[liaison]]s are not possible, i.e. “I hate you (sg.)” is ''je '''te''' hais'', not ''je '''t’'''hais''.\n* In Canadian French, the past historic is used as the present tense for the first, second, and third person singular subject pronouns. Also, the \"h\" is not aspirated, therefore making elisions possible. For example: \"I hate you\" is \"je t'haïs.\" Note that this usage is vernacular and not standard. Some Canadian French speakers may even say \"je t'haguis\", which is also nonstandard and considered even more informal/basilectal than \"je t'haïs.\"\n* In Louisiana, the \"h\" retains its pronunciation as the consonant /h/.\n\n====Conjugation====\n{{fr-conj-auto}}\n\n","alt":[],"syn":[],"type":"verb","forms":[{"mod":"inf","aux":["avoir"],"pronom":false,"impers":false}],"trans":["to hate","to hate","to hate","to hate","to hate"],"group":2,"conj":[{"mod":"indc","tenses":[{"tense":"pres","forms":[["je ha","is"],["tu ha","is"],["il ha","it"],["nous ha","ïssons"],["vous ha","ïssez"],["ils ha","ïssent"]]},{"tense":"pass-c","forms":[["j'ai ha","ï"],["tu as ha","ï"],["il a ha","ï"],["nous avons ha","ï"],["vous avez ha","ï"],["ils ont ha","ï"]]},{"tense":"impf","forms":[["je ha","ïssais"],["tu ha","ïssais"],["il ha","ïssait"],["nous ha","ïssions"],["vous ha","ïssiez"],["ils ha","ïssaient"]]},{"tense":"pqpf","forms":[["j'avais ha","ï"],["tu avais ha","ï"],["il avait ha","ï"],["nous avions ha","ï"],["vous aviez ha","ï"],["ils avaient ha","ï"]]},{"tense":"pass-s","forms":[["je ha","ïs"],["tu ha","ïs"],["il ha","ït"],["nous ha","ïmes"],["vous ha","ïtes"],["ils ha","ïrent"]]},{"tense":"pass-a","forms":[["j'eus ha","ï"],["tu eus ha","ï"],["il eut ha","ï"],["nous eûmes ha","ï"],["vous eûtes ha","ï"],["ils eurent ha","ï"]]},{"tense":"futr","forms":[["je ha","ïrai"],["tu ha","ïras"],["il ha","